# SDLC Role-Aware Coding Rules

These rules are auto-attached when Cursor opens code/test files. Purpose: even when working OUTSIDE the dispatcher loop (ad-hoc edits in main chat), Composer should behave like the right SDLC agent for that file's role.

## Mode detection

| File pattern | Implied role | Quality bar |
|---|---|---|
| `src/**` (production code) | `dev` / `fe-dev` | AC traceability, BR coverage, lint pass |
| `tests/**`, `*.spec.*`, `*.test.*` | `qa` | TC â†” AC mapping, ISTQB technique tag |
| `*.review.md`, PR descriptions | `reviewer` | Risk flags, AC list, TC adequacy |
| `*.adr.md`, `docs/adr/**` | `sa` | Trade-off matrix, alternatives |

## Universal coding discipline (all roles)

1. **Intel-first (token-tiered)** â€” Before adding/modifying auth, RBAC, or routes: base-tier reads `docs/intel/_snapshot.md` first (~5-7K tokens, 95% coverage); fall back to canonical `actor-registry.json` + `permission-matrix.json` only when snapshot stale, missing, or judgment needs full detail (pro-tier). Use canonical role slugs. Never invent.
2. **Feature-state aware** â€” When editing inside `docs/modules/M-NNN-{slug}/features/F-NNN-{slug}/` workspace (CD-22 nested path): read `_feature.md` first. Use `Bash("ai-kit sdlc resolve --kind feature --id F-NNN")` to find canonical location. If `status != done` and current-stage doesn't match the file you're editing â†’ warn user about pipeline state mismatch.
3. **AC tagging** â€” Every meaningful function/class change should reference AC-NNN in commit message OR inline comment if non-obvious.
4. **No silent scope creep** â€” If user asks for X but the file edit needs Y for correctness, surface Y as a separate question instead of bundling.

## Role: dev (`src/**` production)

- Implement ONE acceptance criterion per logical change unit
- Test next to source: every new function with branching logic gets unit test in same PR
- Verdict format on completion: `Ready for QA â€” covers AC-{ids}, BR-{ids}; tests added: {count}`

## Role: qa (`tests/**`)

- Each test file header comment must reference the AC ID(s) it validates
- Use ISTQB technique tags: `// @technique: BVA | EP | DT | ST | EG`
- Negative-case parity: at least one negative test per acceptance criterion
- Verdict format: `Pass â€” {N} tests, {coverage}% AC coverage` or `Fail â€” gaps: {list}`

## Role: reviewer (`*.review.md`, PR description draft)

- List ALL AC IDs touched (do not generalize "covers requirements")
- Flag: missing tests, missing rollback plan (for migrations), missing observability hooks
- Verdict labels: `Approved` | `Approved with follow-ups` | `Changes requested` | `Blocked`

## Role: sa (`docs/adr/**`, `*.adr.md`)

- Use ADR template: Context â†’ Decision â†’ Alternatives â†’ Consequences â†’ Reversibility
- Quantify trade-offs (latency, cost, complexity) â€” never vague "easier"
- Cite at least one DEDUP source (CT 34 Â§6) before introducing new platform/library

## Cache-aware editing

When editing files under `.cursor/agents/` or `.cursor/skills/**/SKILL.md`:
- DO NOT reorder field names in agent prompt header blocks (breaks prompt cache)
- Run `python ~/.cursor/skills/cache-lint/lint.py --path {file} --strict` before commit
- Append-only when adding fields to FROZEN_HEADER
- Field naming: kebab-case lowercase

## Telemetry awareness

If `.cursor/telemetry/{feature-id}.jsonl` exists for the feature this file belongs to:
- Quick-glance recent telemetry before suggesting changes (look for stage retries, cache misses)
- Surface anomalies in your response (e.g., "telemetry shows 3 reworks at qa-wave-1 â€” consider broader test scope")

## Linkage to pipeline

- These rules apply EVEN when user works directly with Composer (no dispatcher loop active)
- They mirror agent discipline so pipeline-vs-ad-hoc work converges in style
- For multi-stage work, prefer `/resume-feature {id}` over ad-hoc Composer turns
